{
  "answer": "**Yama Smṛti, Chapter 2.**\n\nThe first verse prescribes the described punishment for a Brahmin (or one) who has abandoned his sacred fire:\n\n> With his body smeared with ashes and fumigated with the hair and bones of a corpse, / the king, having confiscated all his property, should banish from the kingdom the one who has abandoned his sacred fire.[^1]\n\nThe immediately following, adjacent verse prescribes the described punishment for 'the man who violates convention':\n\n> Being fanned with the hair of a corpse, his head adorned with a garland of it, / the king should make the man who violates convention go naked.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Yama Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/02/translation/#p-c0845b).\n[^2]: Yama Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/02/translation/#p-05b685).",
